Patch Set 6:

May I know the context about why there's a dotted line between _nova_ client and glance_store, I see it's talking about direct location accessing, but I'm not sure why novaclient trigger it, have we planned that? AFAIK, some discussions was planned such project which needs to direct access bits could leverage glance_store directly, e.g. nova call glance_store..  I'd like to take this opportunity to make sure our current plan/trend.

Patch Set 6:

Hello, Zhi! Yes, I remember we were talking about nova's direct access to glance_store and it's mentioned in the BP https://blueprints.launchpad.net/glance/+spec/create-store-package "allow other projects - like Nova - to use it for accessing images directly or other purposes", but afaik it's not done yet.

I decided to include this proposal to the doc (as a dotted line), because I supposed it would be implemented in the near future.

Let's talk about it on tomorrow's meeting - it will be cool to have this feature in OpenStack. If you need some help you can count on me!

Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

This needs some more changes.

According to your definitions, DAL is an interface to interact with persistent storage backend (that sounds more like Image data stores).

1. Registry does not talk to them.

2. DAL and glance_store are equivalent

3. Glance API or Glance registry, both can talk to DB

4. glance_store also perform AuthN/AuthZ

5. Glance API does not perform AuthN, token is passed in from the user. It only does AuthZ.

6.Let's avoid glanceclient related information in this architecture. The client is an alternate way to talk to the REST API.

Patch Set 7:

Thanks for working on this Olena, it's a really important and good addition!

Patch Set 7:

Patch Set 8: Code-Review+1

Nikhil, we get DAL as Data Access Layer from official Sahara documentation where it means layer between server and DB. http://docs.openstack.org/developer/sahara/architecture.html

Wikipedia says that this is "A data access layer (DAL) in computer software, is a layer of a computer program which provides simplified access to data stored in persistent storage of some kind, such as an entity-relational database."

I agree with you that it's not a fully correct term so we decided to change it to "Database abstraction layer" which is surprisingly DAL too, and means "A database abstraction layer is an application programming interface which unifies the communication between a computer application and databases" (c) wikipedia.

Your remaining comments were also taken into account.
